author: Lucky Larry
title: Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center in Athens Reopens After Repairs - NewsBreak
text:
By Lucky Larry ,
54 minutes ago
( Athens, Texas ) The Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center in Athens , Texas, is once again reeling in both first-time and long-time anglers.
After being closed for two years and going through an $8.5 million renovation project, the Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center celebrated its grand reopening on July 1, 2025, but it was a short-lived grand reopening because it suddenly closed its gates to the public on Friday, August 8.
Download the KTYL Mobile App Now After two months of being closed, the Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center in Athens is now open and once again welcoming guests and introducing them to the wonderful world of fishing.
Why the Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center Closed Again After reopening in July, it was discovered during a roof replacement job that a metal structural support beam in the visitor’s center behind an educational display, which was not a part of the renovation, had become corroded and was a potential hazard to the facility. Texas Parks and Wildlife and the Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center management decided to close the facility out of caution so that work could be completed.
Safety Repairs Complete — Gates Reopen in Athens Now that the work is completed, the unique facility held a grand re-reopening of sorts on October 8 as the gates once again opened to guests so that they can learn more about the fish of Texas and cast a line in a stock pond without the need for a fishing license.
READ MORE –> 5 East Texas Lakes Named Best For Fishing In The State Of Texas
What Visitors Can Experience Now East Texans and Texans are now able to catch a fish, go on a hatchery tour, hop on a tram tour, check out the Hall of Fame, walk the Wetlands Trail, view the Gallery Tanks, visit the conservation center, and most importantly, FISH! Don’t worry about acquiring any fishing gear; it’s all on site and free to use, including bait. However, if you have your own rod and reel, you’re welcome to tie on that hook, cast it out in the pond, and set that hook.
Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center Hours and Admission The Texas Freshwater Fisheries Center is currently operating on its fall and winter schedule and is open Wednesday through Saturday from 9a to 4p and Sunday from 1p-4p. It’s $5.50 for ages 17 and up, with discounted prices for younger visitors, and the facility does offer a season pass.
List of the Most Beautiful Lakes Found in Texas Texas has some stunning lakes! Here are some of the most beautiful ones: Gallery Credit: Billy Jenkins Photo by Dale Honeycutt on Unsplash Lake Travis Crystal-clear water, rolling hills, and epic sunsets near Austin. Photo by Luis Olmos on Unsplash Lake Amistad Pristine blue water and dramatic limestone cliffs on the Texas-Mexico border. Photo by Braden Egli on Unsplash Possum Kingdom Lake Famous for the "Hell's Gate" cliffs and scenic beauty. Photo by Karson on Unsplash Inks Lake Gorgeous pink granite outcroppings and calm waters perfect for kayaking. Photo by Megan Bucknall on Unsplash Lady Bird Lake A serene, urban lake in the heart of Austin with amazing skyline views. Photo by MJ Tangonan on Unsplash Canyon Lake Known as the "Jewel of Texas Hill Country," with breathtaking blue-green waters. Photo by Bryan Dickerson on Unsplash Lake Bob Sandlin A peaceful East Texas lake with great fishing, beautiful forests, and stunning fall colors. Photo by Kelly Sikkema on Unsplash Lake Texoma One of the largest reservoirs in the U.S., great for boating and fishing. Photo by Aaron Burden on Unsplash Caddo Lake A mystical lake with cypress trees draped in Spanish moss. Photo by Bryan Dickerson on Unsplash Medina Lake Stunning turquoise water surrounded by rolling hills.
Some of the Most Polluted Lakes in Texas Here’s a list of some of the most polluted lakes in Texas, highlighting various environmental concerns: Gallery Credit: Billy Jenkins Photo courtesy of youtube.com/oneadvantureatatime 14. Lake Meredith (Panhandle) Located in the Texas Panhandle, Lake Meredith has faced issues with declining water levels and water quality due to agricultural runoff and drought conditions. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/fox4news 13. Lake Worth (Fort Worth) Lake Worth has a history of industrial pollution and sediment contamination. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/texasparksandwildlife 12. Lake Arrowhead (Wichita County) Serving as a water supply for Wichita Falls, Lake Arrowhead has experienced challenges with blue-green algae blooms. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/2131studios 11. Lake Granbury (Hood County) Lake Granbury has dealt with issues related to elevated bacteria levels and nutrient pollution. 10. Lake Tawakoni (Northeast Texas) This reservoir has been affected by nutrient pollution and algal blooms. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/davidmart2 9. Lake Ray Hubbard (Dallas County) Located near Dallas, Lake Ray Hubbard has faced pollution challenges from urban runoff and wastewater discharges. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/abc13houston 8. Lake Conroe (Montgomery County) Lake Conroe has experienced issues with invasive aquatic vegetation and nutrient pollution. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/texasparksandwildlife 7. Lake Livingston (East Texas) As one of the largest reservoirs in Texas, Lake Livingston has been impacted by nutrient loading from agricultural runoff. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/yogeshrai 6. Lake Houston (Houston) Serving as a primary water source for Houston, Lake Houston faces challenges from urban runoff, industrial discharges, and stormwater pollution. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/kvuetv 5. Lady Bird Lake (Austin) Lady Bird Lake has been battling recurring outbreaks of harmful blue-green algae since 2019. These algae blooms are fueled by nutrient runoff and warmer temperatures, posing risks to pets and humans. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/thecowboyexperience 4. Lake Travis (Near Austin) Lake Travis has experienced issues with harmful blue-green algae (cyanobacteria), which can produce dangerous toxins. In 2024, a dog died after swimming in the lake near Point Venture. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/timesrecordnews 2. Lake Wichita (Wichita Falls) Lake Wichita has suffered from silt accumulation, drought, and algae blooms, leading to high total dissolved solids (TDS) and cloudy water. It has been ranked among the dirtiest lakes in the U.S. 3. Lake Buchanan (Central Texas) Situated near Burnet, Lake Buchanan has been identified as one of the dirtiest lakes in Texas due to pollution concerns. Photo courtesy of youtube.com/oilfieldwitness 1. Lake Boehmer (Pecos County) An artificial lake formed from abandoned oil wells, Lake Boehmer contains water three times saltier than seawater and sulfate levels 25 times the legal limit for drinking water.
UPDATED: These are the 7 Most Dangerous Lakes in Texas According to AZ Animals there are a few lakes you should probably take off your list to visit, or at the very least be visited with extreme caution. State records reveal that more than 300 people drown in Texas each year. Canva Lake Conroe "Lake Conroe has ranked top of the list of deadliest lakes in Texas since 2000. Between 2010 and 2020, the Texas Parks & Wildlife Department reported 26 deaths at Lake Conroe from boat-related accidents and drowning." Canva Lake Travis "Lake Travis is one of the most visited and most dangerous lakes in Texas. In ranking lakes in Texas for accidental fatalities. Lake Travis was ranked No. 1 in 2011 and tied for second place for total deaths over the years 2000 to 2015.
In 2018, six people drowned in Lake Travis out of 29 total boating deaths reported across Texas that year. Over the past several decades, more than 17 people have died of boat-related incidents on Lake Travis, and some others have disappeared into the depths of the lake, never to be seen again." Canva Lewisville Lake "State figures from 1995 to 2000 show that there were seven reported boating-related deaths, 37 accidents, 24 injuries, and 21 other water fatalities. According to a local news agency, there have been a total of 87 accidental deaths on Lake Lewisville in the past 20 years. " Canva Canyon Lake "Canyon Lake is a reservoir on the Guadalupe River in the Texas Hill Country, approximately 30 miles west of San Marcos. Over the years, more than 10 people have died on Canyon Lake, with officials reporting that they typically have three to four fatalities reported along the lake each year ." Canva Cedar Creek Lake "The 32,000-acre Cedar Creek Lake is a reservoir located about 50 miles southeast of Dallas. Over 15 people have been recorded to have died on Cedar Creek Lake, according to the 2000 to 2015 state records." Canva Joe Pool Lake "With recorded drownings in the lake hitting double digits (about 14 in total from 2000 to 2015 ), Joe Pool Lake in Cedar Hill State Park was once considered to be one of the most dangerous lakes in Texas. Additionally, Walnut Creek, identified as a creek that flows into Joe Pool Lake tested positive for elevated levels of a potentially dangerous bacteria. Due to this, the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality considers that recreational use of the lake is not advised." Canva Lake Livingston "Lake Livingston is approximately 70 miles north of Houston. Reports stated that 20 people have died of boating-related incidents on Lake Livingston since the year 2000.
The Texas Department of State Health Services also found that some species of fish in Lake Livingston had elevated levels of dioxins and polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) that would pose a risk to human health if people were to consume those fishes."
Here are the 10 Most Snake Infested Lakes in Texas Given that the Lone Star State has the largest number of snakes than any other U.S. state, it's good to be aware while enjoying our Texas lakes. Gallery Credit: Tara Holley Wikimedia Commons Lake Livingston Located NE of Houston, Texas, Lake Livingston is home to quite a few snakes. Thankfully most are non-venomous water snakes. Rat snakes are also spotted here. Lake Fork The Lake Fork Reservoir is right here in East Texas and is quite well-known for great bass fishing, a fave ETX pastime. However, it's good to keep a close eye on your surroundings.
There are water and rat snakes, which are non-venomous. BUT, do keep in mind that copperheads and timber rattlesnakes make their home here. Lake Ray Roberts Lake Ray Roberts is quite lovely, as you can see. In Denton county, many love to visit for fishing and general recreation. It is also enjoyed by rattlesnakes and water snakes, however. Caddo Lake Ah, the haunting beauty of Caddo Lake... it looks like something out of a movie, doesn't it? Yep. However, this movie definitely features cottonmouths and copperheads as supporting actors. Inks Lake I wasn't familiar with this lake, actually. According to A-Z-Animals.com, "Inks Lake is a popular lake located in the Edwards Plateau on the Colorado River [...] Considering the plateau’s placement, it’s no surprise that it’s a snake hotspot and that many of these snakes are found in and around Inks Lake." Lake Texoma As one might glean from its name, Lake Texoma sits on the OK-TX border. Lots of folks love to fish and recreate here. It is also home to quite a few species of snakes which include rat and water snakes and the venomous copperhead. Amistad International Reservoir This lake sits on the Texas border with Mexico--close to Del Rio, Texas. Pretty, isn't it? Well, rattlesnakes, garter snakes, and others think so, too. Be aware. :) Lake Corpus Christi This southern Texas lake is home to cottonmouths, rat snakes, and several others. Toldeo Bend Reservoir On the Texas border with Louisiana, Toledo Bend Reservoir is a popular place for fishing and other lake fun. Snakes to be aware of here include cottonmouths and copperheads. Sam Rayburn Reservoir Another great Texas lake known for fishing, it's also the watery abode for water snakes. Although less common, the area is home for copperheads and timber rattlesnakes.
